See comment by Ken S. 

&gt; The GrantedAuthority &quot;VALIDATING&quot; you are testing is just an authority, but you are testing for &quot;ROLE_VALIDATING&quot; in the annotation. I&#39;m not sure if @Secured accepts authorities, all examples I found were roles. You might want to test @PreAuthorize(&quot;hasAuthority(&#39;VALIDATING&#39;)&quot;) instead or rename the authority to &quot;ROLE_VALIDATING&quot; if you want to use roles.  Ken S 24 mins ago

For those following the change I made was either switching to hasAuthority and the @PreAuthorize annotation. 
OR
I changed my userDetailsService:

    Collection&lt;GrantedAuthority&gt; authorities = new ArrayList&lt;GrantedAuthority&gt;();
		authorities.add(new SimpleGrantedAuthority(String.format(&quot;ROLE_%s&quot;, user.getStatus())));

Related: &lt;https://stackoverflow.com/questions/37615034/spring-security-spring-boot-how-to-set-roles-for-users/50533455&gt;

Instead of adding the prefix &quot;ROLE&quot; to authority and using @Secured , you can use  another annotations:  
    @PreAuthorize(&quot;AnyAuthority(&#39;some-authority&#39;)&quot;)  
If you mean to determine several authorities, you can annotate the method by:  
    @PreAuthorize(&quot;hasAnyAuthority({&#39;some-authority&#39;, &#39;read&#39;})&quot;)

In my case, I was converting from Spring Framework to Spring Boot. Apparently Spring Boot increased the strictness of its annotation syntax. Spring Framework was able to parse this syntax to recognize two different roles:

    @PreAuthorize(&quot;hasAnyRoles(&#39;foo, bar&#39;)&quot;)

but Spring Boot does not. Spring Boot required me to add more apostrophes:

    @PreAuthorize(&quot;hasAnyRoles(&#39;foo&#39;, &#39;bar&#39;)&quot;)

